🚨September 2023 Market Update for Toronto ✨📊

The effects of elevated borrowing costs, soaring inflation, the prevailing uncertainty regarding future Bank of Canada actions, and a deceleration in economic growth persistently influenced Greater Toronto Area (GTA) home sales in September. Nevertheless, even with an improved supply of listings, the average selling price witnessed a year-over-year increase.

Below are the highlights from TRREB’s Market Update Report ⬇️

✅Detached home sales in Toronto were up 11.8% year-over-year with an average price up by 8.5%, while semi-detached home sales in Toronto were down by 11.1% year-over-year with the average price up by 5.9%. 🏡

✅Sales of townhomes in Toronto were up by 2.9% year-over-year, and the average sale price was up by 5.1%. Condo sales were down by 2.3%, with the average price decreasing by 4.9%. 🏙

✅”The short and medium-term outlooks for the GTA housing market are very different. In the short term, the consensus view is that borrowing costs will remain elevated until mid-2024, after which they will start to trend lower. This suggests that we should start to see a marked uptick in demand for ownership housing in the second half of next year, as lower rates and record population growth spur an increase in buyers'' - TRREB President Paul Baron.
